            "explanation": "The length of the muscle fiber at the onset of contraction which is required to attain maximum active tension is known as resting length. Resting length is also known as the optimum length. It is about 2um. At this length, there is a maximal overlap between the actin and myosin fibers and therefore, the maximum number of cross-bridge binding sites are formed. Passive tension is the tension in a muscle when it is not stimulated. Total tension is the tension developed when a muscle contracts isometrically in response to a maximal stimulus. Active tension = Total tension - Passive tension When the muscle fiber contracts, the active tension developed is proportional to the number of cross-bridges between the actin and myosin fibers. Hence, at the resting length, maximum active tension is produced and the muscle fiber contracts with a maximum force of contraction.",
