            "correctIndex": 0,
            "explanation": "Among the given options, the frequency of 'slow waves' is maximum in the ileum (8/min). Normal intestinal motility is determined by two patterns of electrical activity - slow waves and spike potentials. Slow waves, also known as basic electrical rhythm are partial depolarizations of smooth muscle cells, spreading along the GIT. They originate from the interstitial cells of Cajal. The smooth muscles are in a hyperpolarized state, having a resting membrane potential of -50 to -60mV. These waves are not action potentials themselves and they do not cause any contractions. Slow waves raise the membrane potential by 5-15mV, bringing it closer to the threshold enabling spike potential (true action potential) to occur. Therefore, they set the basic rhythm of GIT. i. a",
